---
/** Personal finance: when can I retire — same engine as FIRE, framed by age. */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import FireCalculator from '../../components/calculators/FireCalculator.tsx';
import { projectToTarget } from '../../lib/personal-finance';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = projectToTarget({ currentAge: 40, currentSavings: 200000, monthlyContribution: 2000, annualReturn: 0.06, annualExpenses: 60000, withdrawalRate: 0.04 });
---

<Base
  title="When can I retire? Calculator 2026"
  description="The age your savings can replace your income. Set your balance, contributions and target retirement income to see when work becomes optional."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Personal finance · retirement</p>
    <h1>When can I retire?</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Retirement is not a fixed age — it is the moment your savings can pay your bills without you. This finds that year on your numbers.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    The question "when can I retire?" has a precise answer: when your portfolio is large enough that a safe
    withdrawal covers the income you want. Enter your savings, what you add each month, and your target
    retirement income, and this projects the age you cross that line.
  </p>

  <FireCalculator client:load mode="retire" />

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>Someone at 40 with {formatMoney(200000)} saved, adding {formatMoney(2000)}/month, wanting {formatMoney(60000)}/year at a 6% return:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Value</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Nest egg needed (4% of {formatMoney(60000)})</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.target)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Years from now</td><td>{ex.yearsToTarget}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Retirement age</td><td>{ex.ageAtTarget}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Portfolio at retirement</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.projectedAtTarget)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    A {formatMoney(60000)} income needs a {formatMoney(ex.target)} nest egg under the 4% rule — reached in
    {' '}{ex.yearsToTarget} years, at age {ex.ageAtTarget} on these assumptions. Social Security, a pension, or
    part-time income would lower the target and pull that age earlier.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does this include Social Security?</h3>
    <p>No — it projects savings only, which is the conservative view. Any Social Security or pension income
      reduces how much your portfolio has to cover, so your real retirement age is likely earlier than the pure
      savings number shown here.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What return should I assume?</h3>
    <p>A portfolio getting more conservative near retirement often assumes 5–6% rather than the 7% a
      stock-heavy portfolio might. Lower is safer for planning; the calculator lets you test both.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What if the number says "never"?</h3>
    <p>It means the contributions and return you entered do not reach the target within 70 years — usually a sign
      the target income is high relative to savings. Raising the monthly contribution is the fastest lever.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/fire-calculator/">FIRE calculator</a> — the same math, framed by years</li>
    <li><a href="/retirement-withdrawal-calculator/">Retirement withdrawal tax</a> — what withdrawals cost in tax</li>
    <li><a href="/self-employed-retirement-calculator/">Self-employed retirement</a> — SEP and solo 401(k) limits</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">Savings-only projection on a steady assumed return; excludes Social Security and pensions. An illustration, not a promise. Not financial advice.</p>
</Base>
